properties.NAME: Chain Lakes
properties.NOTES: Former Alberta Forest Recreation Area.  Transferred to Alberta Parks in 1996.
properties.Public Story: I have been going to Chain Lakes since a young child. My father would take me fishing, while my mother watched. Now, 30 years later, I watched my 5 year old son catch his first fish with his grandfather. What my father doesn't know is that he's not very good at fishing... catching fish rarely happens with him! My son's fish was caught after he wandered to a man fishing nearby who has several fish in a bucket. My son asked him what he was using and then asked to be given a cast with the lure he was using. My son cast by my father and before I could blink, he was relying in a lovely trout!
properties.Words that describe the park: peaceful, beautiful, restorative, unique, rare, special
properties.Additional Stories: I had a cabin at Island Lake and we would often go to Chain Lakes in the summer for fishing (no boats allowed); the fall for the deer and blueberry picking and in the winter to skidoo through the lakes. The stars were so visible. We often came across campers in all seasons. One winter it was a couple living in a tent with a stove for warmth. It was lovely. We saw a beautiful owl and on our way back we saw about 15 cows running across the road and jumping a fence. There were ospreys and herons. It left a lasting impression which I think about often.

properties.NAME: Bleriot Ferry
properties.NOTES: Former Alberta Transportation Highway Wayside Campsite.  Transferred to Alberta Parks in 1983.
properties.Public Story: Discovered this gem last year after my friends mother passed away suddenly. We were looking for somewhere in the badlands to get away for a night and stubble across Bleriot Ferry. We spent one night there in the shadow of the Coulee's and a stones throw away from the Red Deer River. It was a great place to help him collect his thoughts and just be. We climbed to the top of the coulee's that night to watch the sunset and the whole experience really helped my friend develop some peace to deal with his moms passing.
properties.Words that describe the park: peaceful, beautiful, accessible, family, history, connection, unique, memorable, enticing, wonderful, wild, youth, friendly operator
properties.Additional Stories: -- I proposed to my wife here after crossing the ferry and cycling up the canyon on the other side. It's a spot that is very important to us.    -- My grandfather ran this ferry. My father, and our entire family, have an indescribable emotional connection to this entire  area. The thought of it not being cared for is incredibly upsetting. Let me know how I can help.    --  We _just_ discovered this park last month on our way home from Drumheller. We're in our 50's. I always loved camping but my partner has resisted his whole life. Finally gave it a go this summer since there were few other options, and loved it! The ferry ride was such a highlight! We were especially moved by the Bleriot history since we are originally from Quebec and French Canadian. This was going to be our destination for next year!    -- We chose this beautiful, quiet place for our first camping trip with our infant daughter on Easter weekend, 1999.  I remember breaking sticks for the campfire and she thought that was hilarious.  We returned many times while she was growing up, often with friends.  I'd like to go back again. It makes me very sad and angry that this campground is being taken away from us by a very short-sighted and mean-spirited government.      --I really enjoyed taking the Bleriot Ferry with the family the fall of 2018. The ferry operator was very friendly and had many lovely stories to share during the short ferry ride in this beautiful area. I really hope the ferry will continue to operate in the future and that the beautiful surrounding will be protected from environmental disturbance.      --As a teenager (14 to 16) in Drumheller, from 1971 - 1973 we would tent camp along the southwest side,  downstream of the Bleriot Ferry on long weekends: Victoria Day, Canada Day, Heritage Day. It would often be packed, sometimes 3-400 people along that side, many families from Calgary. As teenage boys will do, we would try to introduce ourselves to teenage girls from Calgary. We partook in many other activities as well -- not all so suitable for your stories. Some of our cohort had Yamaha 125 dirt bikes -- always quite terrifying to ride behind someone else; one year, someone brought their pellet gun -- also somewhat terrifying, however a crack shot he was. Camping was quite different then with no electricity. More tent trailors and tents than motor homes.  It was a beautiful place to camp in the shadow of Cotton Woods along the Red Deer River.

properties.NAME: Chin Coulee
properties.NOTES: Former Alberta Transportation Highway Wayside Campsite.  Transferred to Alberta Parks in 1983.
properties.Public Story: Chin Coulee is a common waterhole for various activities for the residents which live in the area. I have memories going there with my family when I was young, with friends as a teenager and now to take photos of the stars and the sunset. It holds good memories of flying of tubes. Clinging to the bridge as a semi drives by and catching my first fish by myself.

properties.NAME: Riverlot 56
properties.Public Story: I would take my old dog to Riverlot 56 all of the time. On her last day alive I took her there so she could enjoy the smells one last time. It holds such a special place in my heart, and I would be devastated if I could never go there again.
properties.Additional Stories: I have wonderful memories of cross country skiing and walking in the beautiful Riverlot 56 Natural Area. While cross country skiing there one dark evening last winter with friends,  we saw two moose on the trail. We ended up going back the way we came to give them space.

properties.NAME: Mesa Butte
properties.Public Story: When my partner and I first visited the province of Alberta from our home in Ontario we decided to visit Mesa Butte and go hiking. It was on these trails that we were stunned by the shear beauty of this province, the foothills, the Rockies and we made the decision to uproot our lives and make the move to Alberta. We've now lived here for almost 3 years and my heart would break if I knew that, not only would this place be delisted/closed, but that the land may be open to development/sale.

properties.NAME: Sibbald Lake
properties.Public Story: I love this area and the campgrounds around it.  The little lake is a perfect tiny watering hole for swimming.  The wildflowers around here are amazing.  And it's such a quiet area.

properties.NAME: Lundbreck Falls
properties.NOTES: Originally designated in 1932 as a Provincial Park.  De-regulated 1958.  Re-established in 1986 as a Provincial Rec. Area.
properties.Public Story: Lots of local kids would have birthday parties at the Falls in summertime.  My grandma used to tell me stories about the dances they used to have there and the paths she used to walk to get there.

properties.NAME: Cataract Creek
properties.Public Story: This area is beautiful for biking in spring before the highway opens. I would frequently bike down the highway until I found an area with a spot that looked nice to hike. The bike in itself never gets old - the views are unparalleled and the hikes give you even greater views. On one occasion, I ended up on top of a ridge near here on a cloudy day, only to start hearing a strange buzzing noise. It turned out to be my watch, which was vibrating due to all the static in the air! Keep in mind we'd hiked probably 5 hours up at this point. My partner and I high-tailed it off the ridge immediately, for fear of a lightning strike, and that has got to be the most stressful experience I've had on a ridge. On the way down, we had to duck into a band of trees as it started hailing. Fortunately it didn't last long and we were able to finish (running) making our way down the mountain. The down trek only took 2 hours! Always makes for a good story though
properties.Words that describe the park: electric, weather, hike, accessible, hiking, fishing
properties.Additional Stories: I love this campground. It is close to Calgary and easy to get to. I have camped in tents and done the adjacent hikes (Mount Burke and Raspberry Ridge). Other people there were great and the campground manager was very friendly and helpful when I needed help determining how to pay and purchasing fire wood.

properties.NAME: Highwood
properties.Public Story: I learned to identify a large number of Alpine flora here.  The diversity of species in such an easily accessible space is irreplaceable.

properties.NAME: Prairie Creek
properties.NOTES: Former Alberta Forest Recreation Area.  Transferred to Alberta Parks in 1996.
properties.Public Story: My inlaws camped there when my husband was little and we continued the tradition going 3 or more times per year. Stall 6 is our favorite. There are three spruce trees in a clump next to the site that we have watched grow from a foot or two tall to well over 15 feet. We call them the three sisters.

properties.NAME: Indian Graves
properties.Public Story: I hiked around here with the University of Calgary Outdoor club years ago.  Beautiful area.

properties.NAME: Cow Lake
properties.Public Story: Cow Lake is a place that my family does a yearly campout at. I have great memories of last year when my mother, niece and nephew camped there for a couple of days. I really like the area and the campground itself. It's affordable and accessible.

properties.NAME: J.J. Collett
properties.Public Story:
I grew up going to this park, it's one of my favourites and I visit each time I go home to visit my family, around 5-10 times per year. Growing up in the area, I was a member of Brownies in Ponoka for several years, and this is where our group went to learn orienteering, animal tracking, and tree and plant identification.
This is also where my grandparents would take us grandkids to learn an appreciation of the outdoors and the value of exploring our local natural areas. 
Years later, this is where I bring my partner for hiking and picnicking and it's a place that has become very meaningful for both of us.
properties.Words that describe the park: memorable, beautiful, relaxing, diverse, treasure, wildflowers
properties.Additional Stories: I have not visited in a long time but in 1994 as President of the Red Deer River Naturalists we were on an outing with the late Helen Harris, Eileen Ford and others.  The place is so diverse: sandy portions, wetlands, wild flowers, poplar and climax spuce -- whole forest succession. A beautiful Parkland Ecotone. Helen could spot and identify a Harebell , a Lady Slipper, Shooting Stars or a Northern Starflower from 35 metres. Her knowledge was astonishing.  And of course if you visited J.J. Collett two weeks later in mid June (that year) there woudl be all kinds of new wildflowers in bloom through the late spring. One person with us, Eileen Ford, decided we needed to tap this increcible knowlege and started a Flower Focus Groupl  Eileen was so inspired to she took course at Vermillion so she could learn the Latin and went on to lead many outings all over Alberta inspired by Helen Harris. Helen received first Owl Award that RDRN presents to a dedicated member each year in 1999.  Such a diverse, beautiful place.

properties.NAME: Waterton Reservoir
properties.NOTES: Former Alberta Environment camp site/day-use area.  Transferred to Alberta Parks in 1996.
properties.Public Story: i went hiking with my family and after the niki we went to town to look around and eat, once we started we realized it was so small and there weren't any asian places to eat i was disappointed. i mean aside from hiking, going on a boat or eating there isn't anything to do. i wish there would be a water park and more diverse restaurants

properties.NAME: Park Lake
properties.Public Story:
My son took multiple lauding courses on Park Lake through a small, local business. He also got to do a course with his Dad that was a Father's Day present. 
A few years later he taught me kayak safety and how to paddle when we ended up unexpectedly kayaking on the skeleton ocean. The first of the lessons is priceless. But only is he safe (and those with him) on the water, but he had new ways to explore Alberta. Park Lake is a perfect place to learn the basics- calm, close to the city, and much of the year clean enough to swim in.
properties.Words that describe the park: pleasant, fun, memorable, relaxation, community, learning, life, beautiful
properties.Additional Stories: -- I've been swimming and canoeing at park lake since I was a small kid 5/6 years old. (I'm almost 40) and have been keeping the tradition going with my kids. We Always camp at Park lake as that's what my youngest wants for his birthday.  So many of us use this lake and campground. Please dont take it away. We need it. ( human populess)    -- Great place for family summer fun!    --  Park lake has been a part of my life for the last 6+ years. Me and my husband used to take our dogs swimming out there off the boat launch when it was just the 2 of us. Once we had our first child we have made so many memories playing on the beach and swimming out there. Since we’ve had a second child I’d love for her to have the same memories. It is a place we make memories, as a family. We meet our extended family there and friends. It is a place we love, please don’t take it away from us.

properties.NAME: Clifford E. Lee
properties.NOTES: IUCN Category II. Not Reported due to existing subsurface mineral commitments with surface access.
properties.Public Story: When we had a young child learning to walk, the boardwalk at Clifford E. Lee Natural Area was a safe spot to enjoy nature and get out of the city. The Provincial Parks are so much more than the big National Parks little siblings.
properties.Words that describe the park: birding, boardwalk, family, wetlands, stroll, birds, peaceful, treasure, beautiful, nature
properties.Additional Stories: I cannot tell you how many times our family has visited this gem over the years.  From the time our children could make the trek we have visited several times a year looking at tadpoles and dragonfly larvae in the spring, summer strolls on school breaks, enjoying the autumn colours and even going for a walk with friends on an usually warm Christmas break.  Our children did joint Phys Ed and Science class by riding bikes from nearby school and conducting science class here.  A visit from out of town family and friends was not complete without a trip to the Clifford E Lee.      --We needed to escape the stress for a couple of hours in the middle of Covid. Beautiful walk through varied habitats. The kids, 7 and 9 loved it. We want to keep this treasure, so close to the city yet wild and beautiful, protected forever.      --I love bird watching in this beautiful area! GoA this area MUST be protected for future generations!

properties.NAME: Dry Island Buffalo Jump
properties.OC_NAME: Dry Island Buffalo Jump Provincial Park
properties.Park Name: Dry Island Buffalo Jump Provincial Park
properties.Public Story: I take my nieces and nephews to Henry's Shoes (Trochu, great shoe store!) for their grade one shoes and we go to Dry Island Buffalo Jump to spend the afternoon. This is a unique area and they (and I) love the terrain and river.
properties.Words that describe the park: awe-inspiring, exciting, engaging, quiet, family orientated, popular, historic, special, beautiful, unique, magnificent, stunning, breathtaking, fascinating, ecotone, relief, peaceful, specatular, energizing
properties.Additional Stories: -- This is a very popular little campground for families. Kids love to wade in the Red Deer river and play along the shoreline. There is a rope swing hanging off the bridge is is very popular with older kids. An excellent put in spot/take out spot for kayakers and canoeists. Also and great place to camp for overnight river trips on the Red Dee River.     -- The first time I saw it, I thought wow, would I love to take a canoe down the river here.  Years later, I paddled it and it was everything I imagined it to be: a beautiful, historic, special place.  I hope this park is saved so that others can enjoy it, too.    -- Every summer I take my nieces and nephews on adventures. Because there are seven of them, various ages, I double them up and give them a chance to spend time with their cousins, rather than their siblings. For the past few years, one of the most requested adventures is to go to "the place with the river and the mountains". This is Dry Island Buffalo Jump ("mountains" to kids!). We go, play in the river, have a picnic, and explore the park. The kids love it and talk about it all year. This park is less than an hour from where we live and gives us the chance to have a little holiday locally, without spending a lot of money. The topography and history fascinates these children (and me!) and it will break my heart to tell them that we can not go to "the place with the river and the mountains". This place of history and memories should be available to all.      --I had a large dog who only ever stood in the river not a swimmer, he had long hair and on a very hot day early in July we were in the river with our dog when suddenly he began yipping and kind of hopping, very distressed. I waded over to him....he was surrounded by dozens of baby garter snakes jumping up at the water droplets on his long hairs...was the most crazy wonderful thing i had ever seen. Did not know that these snakes swam was sooo kool! However my big big dog was very traumatized as i hailed him back to shore. Love this place.      --In 1994 as Preisdent of the Red Deer River Naturalists we met a group from the Federation of Alberta Naturalists (FAN) then, now Nature Alberta.  I forget her name but there was a lady who lived nearby and was a wealth of local ecological knowledge who met us.  It was a scorcher of a day, at least 30 degrees in early July.  Some of the group headed for the Buffalo Jump some to the Dry Island. I was with the Buffalo Jump group. We were out there at least 4 hours, half way down from the first plateau at 2:30 pm when a lady from Edmonton, a tall angular, in shape, in her mid 70s sprained her ankle. We were in trouble. We would have to carry her back up the hill and back where we started.  As we were deciding what the heck to do a couple of people came by in a canoe. They were drinking and their cell phone was dead.  Fortunately, the University of Calgary Canoe Club were out practicing.  We could then carry her down the hill and one of the canoes took her back upstream where we started. Otherwise, we were really in a bind.     --I have been a regular hiker at Dry Island Buffalo Jump since 1991. I think it is the most spectacular place to hike within an hour's drive of Red Deer. I love this place. On top of the dry island is one of the few places you can find that is completely devoid of mechanical noises. Occasionally I hear a small plane far off in the distance, but because it is so far away and faint, it doesn't feel like an intrusion. I look forward to them fixing the road, as hiking down to the picnic area and back up to the parking lot adds a lot of time to a pleasant hike.

properties.NAME: Coal Lake North
properties.OC_NAME: Coal Lake North Provincial Recreation Area
properties.NOTES: Former Alberta Environment camp site/day-use area.  Transferred to Alberta Parks in 1996.
properties.Park Name: Coal Lake North Provincial Recreation Area
properties.Public Story: We brought some friends with small kids to go canoeing and fishing here.  We chose it because it's the same distance from Edmonton as Islet Lake and Big Lake, but much less crowded. We were rewarded with a sunny and calm weekend paddle and saw many other families enjoying themselves there, too.

properties.NAME: Cartier Creek
properties.NOTES: Former Alberta Forest Recreation Area.  Transferred to Alberta Parks in 1996.
properties.Public Story: The first time I went to Cartier Creek, I took a whitewater canoe course.  We flipped our boat on our very first eddy turn out on the river.  We were such bad students, the instructor took me aside after the first day and recommended that we stick to flatwater. The next day, the instructors flipped their canoe, but we stayed upright and kept paddling our whitewater dreams.  We kayak the Upper Red Deer River regularly now and have stayed at Cartier Creek many times with our clubs and our friends. I caught the biggest trout of my life there.  It's a great resource for fishermen, paddlers and those without RVs who would like to stay in a tent and use the facilities provided by a campground.

properties.NAME: Horburg
properties.NOTES: Former Alberta Forest Recreation Area.  Transferred to Alberta Parks in 1996.
properties.Public Story: There is an excellent whitewater run from Horburg to Rocky Mountain House that is accessed from this campground.  I have enjoyed this as a day trip and an overnighter.  What a special place.

properties.NAME: McLeod River
properties.NOTES: Former Alberta Forest Recreation Area.  Transferred to Alberta Parks in 1996.
properties.Public Story: I experienced my very first whitewater canoe trip in Alberta, here in the spring of 2014.  I didn't have a partner or a whitewater boat, so I got to paddle with the President of the club! It's a very long run, and a very long day trip from Edmonton, so it's best to camp overnight at the campground.

properties.NAME: Wildhay
properties.NOTES: Former Alberta Forest Recreation Area.  Transferred to Alberta Parks in 1996.
properties.Public Story: This is a great place to camp and take some spring whitewater runs on the Wildhay River.  I've been here several times with my canoe club and I hope I get to do it again in the future.

properties.NAME: Pembina Forks
properties.NOTES: Former Alberta Forest Recreation Area.  Transferred to Alberta Parks in 1996.
properties.Public Story: Enjoyed many lovely nature walks in this beautiful area while I was working near Robb many years ago.

properties.NAME: Sherwood Park
properties.Public Story: I've gone for many walks in this area close to my City while enjoying prestine plants and birds.
